<h6 class="kicker">Science</h6>
<p class="summary">Teaching ideas based on New York Times content.</p>
<ul class="refer">
<li><a href="/category/science/">See all in Science Â»</a></li>
<li><a href="/category/lesson-plans/" title="See all Lesson Plans">See all lesson plans Â»</a></li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong><em>Updated: Feb. 18</em></strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">This week we are posting lesson ideas related to the 2014 Winter Games, organized by subject matter. Below, you will find a collection of teaching ideas for science, math and health. On Tuesday we published <a href="//learning.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/02/11/teaching-the-sochi-olympics-history-geography-and-social-studies/">suggestions for history, geography and social studies</a>. On Thursday, we will post a <a href="//learning.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/02/13/teaching-the-sochi-olympics-english-language-arts-journalism-and-fine-arts/">list for English language arts, journalism, media studies and fine arts</a>; and on Friday, we will feature Sochi-inspired examples and writing prompts in our weekly Skills lesson.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Let us know how youâre teaching the Games.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span id="more-142534"></span></p>
<hr/>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>How Do They Do That? </strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Deconstruct the jumps, spins and landings of slopestyle and halfpipe snowboarders and of ski jumpers with the series <a href="//www.nytimes.com/newsgraphics/2014/sochi-olympics/ski-jumping.html">&#8220;Defying, then Exploiting, Gravity.&#8221;</a> Then, explore the interplay between <a href="https://www.nbclearn.com/olympics/cuecard/47284">speed, gravity, and kinetic and potential energy</a> in a typical halfpipe run. Finally, explain the sport of <a href="https://www.nbclearn.com/olympics/cuecard/47272 ">curling</a> using the language of physics. How do the many tiny bumps in the surface of the ice used in curling affect the motion of the stone? Why do curlers sweep the ice? What is momentum exchange, and how is kinetic energy transferred in the sport?</p>
<div class="w480"><figure class="promo media video blog-video "
    data-videoid="100000002695872" data-media-action="modal" data-autoplay="" data-embedded="true" aria-label="media" role="group">
        <span class="visually-hidden">Video</span>

    <figcaption class="caption">
        <h4 class="headline">Olympic Tricks Revealed</h4>
		        <div class="caption-video">
                <div class="summary-credit">
            <p class="summary">Snowboarders and skiers have an extensive vocabulary of spins and flips. Here, Olympic athletes break down their signature tricks.</p>
            <span class="credit video-credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder">
                By Brad Kimbrough, Ben Laffin and Catherine Spangler on                                                    <span class="visually-hidden">Publish Date </span>February 10, 2014.
                            </span>
            <span class="credit photo-credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder">
                                    Photo by Harry How/Getty Images.
                                </span>
        </div>

                    <div class="sharetools-video-container">
                <div id="sharetools-video-tools-100000002695872"
                    class="sharetools sharetools-video-tools">
                    <ul>
                        <li class="sharetool embed-sharetool">
                            <a href="javascript:;" data-share="embed" data-modal-title="">
                                <i class="icon sprite-icon"></i>
                                <span class="sharetool-text ">embed</span>
                            </a>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div id="sharetools-video-inline-100000002695872"
                    class="sharetools sharetools-video-inline"
                    data-shares="facebook|,twitter|"
                    data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/video/sports/olympics/100000002695872/olympic-tricks-revealed.html?action=click&amp;contentCollection=sports&amp;module=blog-video&amp;region=caption&amp;pgtype=article"
