                    data-content-type="video">
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
            </figcaption>
</figure>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Interested in the physics of more sports in the Winter Games?  Then check out the <a href="//www.nytimes.com/interactive/2014/02/11/sports/sochi-2014-interactive-stories.html">full collection of Interactive graphics</a> in The New York Times for <a href="//www.nytimes.com/newsgraphics/2014/sochi-olympics/slopestyle.html">slopestyle snowboarding</a>, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/newsgraphics/2014/sochi-olympics/halfpipe.html">halfpipe snowboarding,</a><br />
<a href="//www.nytimes.com/newsgraphics/2014/sochi-olympics/giant-slalom.html">giant slalom</a> and more. And learn in <a href="//www.nytimes.com/interactive/2014/02/05/sports/olympics/sochi-snowboarding-and-skiing-tricks.html">these 16 short videos</a> about how skiers and snowboarders pull off their jaw-dropping tricks.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">You also might investigate the engineering behind the designs of some of the courses at the Sochi Olympics.  How do the <a href="//www.nytimes.com/newsgraphics/2014/sochi-olympics/luge.html">uphill sections</a> in the luge track help to make it safer? What new challenges do they introduce for athletes on the track? Talk about how physics concepts, such as <a href="//btc.montana.edu/olympics/physbio/physics/phys-intro.html">acceleration, friction</a> and <a href="//www.real-world-physics-problems.com/physics-of-luge.html">gravity,</a> affect performance in the luge competition.  Then, see how <a href="//www.nsf.gov/news/special_reports/winterolympics/index.jsp">the halfpipe is engineered</a> to give riders more airtime.  Engineering pops up again in the conception of <a href="//www.nsf.gov/news/special_reports/winterolympics/compsuits.jsp">speedskating suits</a> meant to minimize friction and maximize a skater&#8217;s aerodynamic performance.  To continue exploring physics, check out our lesson plan <a href="//learning.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/02/10/getting-physical-the-physics-and-other-science-behind-winter-olympic-sports/">&#8220;Getting Physical: The Physics and Other Science Behind Winter Olympic Sports.&#8221;</a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Success at Any Cost?</strong></p>
<div class="w190 right"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/02/04/sports/CITY-SLOPESTYLE-LN/CITY-SLOPESTYLE-articleInline.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/02/04/sports/CITY-SLOPESTYLE-LN/CITY-SLOPESTYLE-articleInline.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/02/04/sports/CITY-SLOPESTYLE-LN/CITY-SLOPESTYLE-articleInline.jpg" id="100000002706483" width="190" height="142" alt="Workers groomed the slopestyle course, about which safety concerns were raised when a snowboarder broke his collarbone. &lt;a href=&quot;//www.nytimes.com/2014/02/04/sports/olympics/snowboard-course-will-change-after-athletes-complain-of-danger.html&quot;&gt;Related Article&lt;/a&gt;"   /><meta itemprop="height" content="142"><meta itemprop="width" content="190"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Workers groomed the slopestyle course, about which safety concerns were raised when a snowboarder broke his collarbone. <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/02/04/sports/olympics/snowboard-course-will-change-after-athletes-complain-of-danger.html">Related Article</a></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Lucas Jackson/Reuters</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">What complaints have athletes had about the <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/02/04/sports/olympics/snowboard-course-will-change-after-athletes-complain-of-danger.html">slopestyle course</a> at Sochi? What hazards have they identified in the course, and how are officials proposing to address them?  How have officials tried to make the luge course <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/02/05/sports/olympics/on-the-luge-safety-built-into-swerves.html">safer?</a>  </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">To address the subject of health, hold a debate over whether itâs worth taking risks to pursue excellence in sports &#8212; especially since, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/02/12/sports/olympics/beside-the-flash-of-gold-a-shadow.html">in some high-risk, high-reward events, it is clearly a question of when injuries will occur, not if</a>. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Choose one of these competitions and explain the science behind the dangers. Then hold a discussion on whether <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2006/06/15/health/15gene.html">genes</a> might play a role in a person&#8217;s willingness to take on risky sports. </p>
<hr/>
<div class="w480"><figure class="promo media video blog-video "
    data-videoid="100000002685534" data-media-action="modal" data-autoplay="" data-embedded="true" aria-label="media" role="group">
        <span class="visually-hidden">Video</span>

    <figcaption class="caption">
        <h4 class="headline">How It Happens | Snowmaking</h4>
		        <div class="caption-video">
                <div class="summary-credit">
            <p class="summary">Machines make snow the same way nature does â only much more quickly, and a lot closer to the ground.</p>
            <span class="credit video-credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder">
                By Aaron Byrd, Leslye Davis and Henry Fountain on                                                    <span class="visually-hidden">Publish Date </span>February 3, 2014.
                            </span>
            <span class="credit photo-credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder">
