            </figcaption>
</figure>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>The Science of Snowmaking</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Ski and snowboard events must go on, even in the absence of natural snow. Check out this video of <a href="//www.nytimes.com/video/science/100000002685534/the-science-of-snowmaking.html">how snowmaking works</a>, then explore the science behind it in depth. What is the relationship between air temperature, humidity and snowmaking? What is the role of dust? Why does snow that forms naturally take on a six-sided crystalline shape, while the artificial variety lacks this structure?  </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Dive deeper into the topic by discussing some of the <a href="//www.outsideonline.com/blog/outdoor-adventure/science/the-environmental-impact-of-making-snow.html">environmental consequences</a> of snowmaking, including <a href="//www.mnn.com/money/sustainable-business-practices/stories/snowmakers-are-saving-ski-resorts-for-now">water usage</a> and the <a href="//green.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/01/11/discolored-slopes-mar-debut-of-snow-making-effort/">controversy</a> over the use of reclaimed wastewater at the Arizona Snowbowl in Flagstaff. Should people be able to make snow anywhere, even in <a href="//wwwp.dailyclimate.org/tdc-newsroom/2014/02/hot-snow-ski">70-degree weather</a>?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>The Future of Winter Olympics? </strong></p>
<div class="w190 right"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/02/09/sunday-review/09SNOWjpSUB-LN/09SNOWjpSUB-articleInline.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/02/09/sunday-review/09SNOWjpSUB-LN/09SNOWjpSUB-articleInline.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/02/09/sunday-review/09SNOWjpSUB-LN/09SNOWjpSUB-articleInline.jpg" id="100000002706488" width="190" height="127" alt="Slopes were closed last month at Fichtelberg mountain in Oberwiesenthal, Germany. &lt;a href=&quot;//www.nytimes.com/2014/02/08/opinion/sunday/the-end-of-snow.html&quot;&gt;Related Article&lt;/a&gt;"   /><meta itemprop="height" content="127"><meta itemprop="width" content="190"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Slopes were closed last month at Fichtelberg mountain in Oberwiesenthal, Germany. <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/02/08/opinion/sunday/the-end-of-snow.html">Related Article</a></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Jan Woitas/European Pressphoto Agency</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The snow on the slopes at Sochi may look pristine and brand new, but officials there began  <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/03/26/sports/olympics/with-weather-concerns-organizers-are-storing-snow-for-winter-olympics-in-sochi-russia.html">stockpiling snow</a> a year ago in preparation for the Olympics. The effort underscores a topic of concern to all ski and snowboard enthusiasts: How will <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/02/08/opinion/sunday/the-end-of-snow.html">climate change affect snow conditions</a> in the future? Talk about some of the specific effects a <a href="//www.nytimes.com/interactive/2014/02/09/sunday-review/postcards-from-milder-winters-recent-and-future.html">warming climate will have on the snowpack</a> on mountains in the eastern and western United States, and what effect it may have on the <a href="//www.climatecentral.org/news/the-winter-olympics-in-a-warming-world-17042">future locations of Winter Olympic Games</a>. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Drug-Free Zones?</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Read about Irina Starykh, the Russian biathlete who <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/01/31/sports/olympics/biathlete-leaves-russian-team-after-testing-positive.html">withdrew from the Olympics after failing a drug test</a>. Then, explore the topic of doping in sports. What is it, and why do athletes, despite rules banning the practice, still use performance-enhancing drugs? Identify some of the substances, such as <a href="//www.deadiversion.usdoj.gov/pubs/brochures/steroids/professionals/index.html">steroids</a>, that are <a href="//www.usada.org/prohibited-list/">banned by the World Anti-Doping Agency</a>, and describe how these <a href="//www.usada.org/effects-peds/">compounds affect the human body</a>. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>The Care and Feeding of Elite Athletes</strong></p>
<div class="w190 right"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/02/09/sports/DOG-NUTRITION-LN/DOG-NUTRITION-articleInline.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/02/09/sports/DOG-NUTRITION-LN/DOG-NUTRITION-articleInline.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/02/09/sports/DOG-NUTRITION-LN/DOG-NUTRITION-articleInline.jpg" id="100000002706593" width="190" height="107" alt="âIf an athleteâs hungry, I donât sleep,â said Alicia Kendig, the dietitian for the United Statesâ womenâs hockey team. She goes by the nickname Nutricia. &lt;a href=&quot;//www.nytimes.com/2014/02/09/sports/olympics/nutritionist-believes-healthy-diet-is-key-to-gold.html&quot;&gt;Related Article&lt;/a&gt;"   /><meta itemprop="height" content="107"><meta itemprop="width" content="190"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">âIf an athleteâs hungry, I donât sleep,â said Alicia Kendig, the dietitian for the United Statesâ womenâs hockey team. She goes by the nickname Nutricia. <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/02/09/sports/olympics/nutritionist-believes-healthy-diet-is-key-to-gold.html">Related Article</a></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> USA Hockey</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">What does it take to fuel an Olympian? How does <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/02/09/sports/olympics/us-ski-teams-can-now-order-in.html">nutrition affect athletic performance</a>? To answer those questions, the United States Women&#8217;s Hockey Team hired a dietician to <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/02/09/sports/olympics/nutritionist-believes-healthy-diet-is-key-to-gold.html">plan its meals</a> and monitor its player&#8217;s health, specifically their levels of hydration and various vitamins.  The American ski and snowboarding teams, likewise, bring along a <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/02/09/sports/olympics/us-ski-teams-can-now-order-in.html">chef to prepare nutritious meals</a> for them. Read the articles, then plan a healthy diet regimen for an Olympic snowboarder or figure skater, taking into account how many <a href="//www.shape.com/fitness/training-plans/which-classic-winter-sports-torch-most-calories">calories</a> athletes might burn in different winter sports.</p>
<hr/>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Update: Feb. 18 | The Sochi Odometer</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Have fun with a real-time interactive called <a href="//sochi2014.nytimes.com/odometer">The Sochi Odometer,</a> which tells the story of this year&#8217;s Games by the numbers with stats on everything from records broken to the total saves in ice hockey to how many athletes cite woodworking as a hobby. Which numbers surprise you most? Why? How could you put that number into context to explain to someone who doesn&#8217;t know the sport why it is surprising? </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Math With Medals</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Use this <a href="//2010games.nytimes.com/medals/map.html">infographic</a> that shows the medal counts from all prior Winter Olympics to explore the performance of countries and regions in the Winter Games.  Start by making some predictions about how many medals each country will win in Sochi, using past data as a model.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Or, pick a country, graph its medal count over time and write a narrative about its historical performance.  For example, create a chart displaying Canada&#8217;s medal counts over the past 90 years.  How does its performance in more recent Olympic competitions compare with earlier games?  What might explain the change?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Use the medal counts to investigate the Olympic &#8220;home field advantage.&#8221;  For each country that has <a href="//www.topendsports.com/events/winter/hosts/index.htm">hosted the winter Olympics,</a> calculate the average number of medals it wins when hosting the games and when it does not.  Do the host nations tend to win more medals?  Do they win more <a href="//www.nytimes.com/interactive/2010/02/10/sports/olympics/winter-goldmedals.html">gold medals</a> in particular?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Look for correlations in medal counts by creating scatter plots of total medals won combined with other data, like a country&#8217;s population, its gross domestic product, or perhaps its average latitude or temperature.  Do countries farther from the Equator perform better in the Winter Games?  How about colder countries?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Check out the <a href="//www.topendsports.com/events/winter/sports/">newer Winter Olympic events</a>.  Which countries have benefited the most from the introduction of these new games?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Money Games</strong></p>
<div class="w190 right"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/01/26/sports/oligarch-LN/oligarch-articleInline.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/01/26/sports/oligarch-LN/oligarch-articleInline.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/01/26/sports/oligarch-LN/oligarch-articleInline.jpg" id="100000002706507" width="190" height="75" alt="Biathletes are among the Russian Olympic competitors who are helped by corporate executives. &lt;a href=&quot;//www.nytimes.com/2014/01/26/sports/olympics/deep-pocket-russians-adopt-teams-chasing-gold.html&quot;&gt;Related Article&lt;/a&gt;"   /><meta itemprop="height" content="75"><meta itemprop="width" content="190"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Biathletes are among the Russian Olympic competitors who are helped by corporate executives. <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/01/26/sports/olympics/deep-pocket-russians-adopt-teams-chasing-gold.html">Related Article</a></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Sven Hoppe/European Pressphoto Agency</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Hosting the Olympics is said to be good for a country&#8217;s economy, but this article about the <a href="//economix.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/08/10/the-elusive-economic-lift-of-the-olympics/">elusive Olympic lift</a> suggests otherwise.  Read about the <a href="//www.tppsochi.ru/en/node/688">local economy</a> of Sochi, then follow up after the games by researching what becomes of the <a href="//www.businessweek.com/articles/2014-01-02/the-2014-winter-olympics-in-sochi-cost-51-billion">$51 billion</a> Russia spent to host them.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Read <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/01/26/sports/olympics/deep-pocket-russians-adopt-teams-chasing-gold.html">this article</a> about how Olympic squads are being adopted by wealthy Russians like Brooklyn Nets owner Mikhail Prokhorov, the sponsor of his home country&#8217;s biathlon team.  Research each teamâs historical performance, and watch to see if this kind of investment pays off. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Hockey Interrupted</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The National Hockey League is <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/07/20/sports/hockey/nhl-stars-to-return-to-olympics-in-sochi-in-2014.html">taking a break</a> from its regular season to allow its players to compete for their home countries in the Winter Olympics.  How might this break affect the athletes&#8217; performance in the professional league?  Chart the regular season <a href="//espn.go.com/nhl/statistics">statistics</a> for hockey players before and after the Olympic break.  Do players who rest during the Olympics enjoy a bump in performance in the N.H.L. season&#8217;s second half?  Do Olympic participants perform worse because of the Olympic extension of their season?  Compare stats from non-Olympic years with pre- and post- Olympic N.H.L. statistics and look for the effect the Winter Games have on hockey&#8217;s biggest stars.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Size and Scope of the Winter Games</strong></p>
<div class="w190 right"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/02/04/sports/olympic-venues-1391570745165-LN/olympic-venues-1391570745165-articleInline.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/02/04/sports/olympic-venues-1391570745165-LN/olympic-venues-1391570745165-articleInline.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/02/04/sports/olympic-venues-1391570745165-LN/olympic-venues-1391570745165-articleInline.jpg" id="100000002706519" width="190" height="102" alt="&lt;a href=&quot;//www.nytimes.com/interactive/2014/02/04/sports/olympic-venues.html&quot;&gt;Related Article&lt;/a&gt;"   /><meta itemprop="height" content="102"><meta itemprop="width" content="190"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text"><a href="//www.nytimes.com/interactive/2014/02/04/sports/olympic-venues.html">Related Article</a></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> The New York Times</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Check out this <a href="//www.nytimes.com/interactive/2014/02/04/sports/olympic-venues.html">imaginitive gallery of images</a> showing what Olympic venues would look like if they were placed in the middle of New York City, and then do some research on the size and scope of events like slopestyle, biathlon and alpine skiing.  See how Olympic hills, trails and tracks might look in the middle of your town by sketching diagrams of the venues next to images of your own local landmarks.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Speed Predictions</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Investigate the Olympic and world records in various events, and use data from past Olympics to predict whether this year&#8217;s Olympians will be even faster on the ice and snow.  For example, you can chart the historical data on events like <a href="//www.olympic.org/speed-skating-1000m-men">Men&#8217;s 1,000 meters in speed skating</a> at Olympic.org, or do your own research on every event from every past Winter Games <a href="//www.olympic.org/olympic-results">here</a>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Graphing the Gold-Medal Run</strong></p>
<div class="w190 right"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/02/08/sports/olympics/mens-slopestyle-1391869074982-LN/mens-slopestyle-1391869074982-articleInline.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/02/08/sports/olympics/mens-slopestyle-1391869074982-LN/mens-slopestyle-1391869074982-articleInline.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/02/08/sports/olympics/mens-slopestyle-1391869074982-LN/mens-slopestyle-1391869074982-articleInline.jpg" id="100000002706618" width="190" height="107" alt="&lt;a href=&quot;//www.nytimes.com/interactive/2014/02/08/sports/olympics/mens-slopestyle.html&quot;&gt;Related Article&lt;/a&gt;"   /><meta itemprop="height" content="107"><meta itemprop="width" content="190"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text"><a href="//www.nytimes.com/interactive/2014/02/08/sports/olympics/mens-slopestyle.html">Related Article</a></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Composite image by The New York Times</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Take a look at these <a href="//www.nytimes.com/interactive/2014/02/08/sports/olympics/mens-slopestyle.html">image sequences</a> of gold-medalist Sage Kotsenburg&#8217;s slopestyle jumps.  Use a dynamic mathematics graphing utility, like <a href="//www.Geogebra.org">Geogebra</a> or <a href="//www.desmos.com">Desmos,</a> to try to re-create the snowboarder&#8217;s path.  </p>
<div id="teaching-standards" class="teaching-standards">
	<div class="stndrd-desc">
		<h4>Standards</h4>
