		<div class="comment-content" style="display:block;">

			<p>As an athlete, nutrition has had a significant role in my life over the past few years, and because of this, the article entitled âMenu for U.S. Womenâs Hockey Team Is About Eating to Win,â written by Jere Longman, truly fascinated me. Due to the fact that Olympic athletes are constantly training and exerting energy left and right, their bodies require insane amounts of fuel in order to ensure that each and every performance is their absolute best. The U.S. womenâs hockey team wisely hired a sports dietician, named Alicia Kendig, for the Sochi Winter Olympic Games to fulfill the duty of making sure that the athletesâ bodies were properly fed and hydrated each day. As a result of the new and improved diet advancements, the team members found it much easier for their bodies to keep up with the aggressive and fast-paced sport and emerge victoriously from multiple games. The American teamâs coach, Katey Stone, reported the effect of Kendigâs extremely beneficial meal plan for the athletes as, âone more piece of the puzzle so that [the team has] an advantage, a little edgeâ (paragraph 5). I find it so intriguing that a few, simple alterations in the athletesâ meal plans made such a tremendous difference in their ability to power through games with lots of energy and bring home more wins! Before the American hockey team versed Finland in the womenâs tournament, they âate a breakfast of scrambled eggs, chopped baked potatoes, oatmeal, cereal, strawberries and blueberries,â and âtwo hours later, a pregame snack included bananas and more oatmeal fortified with peanut butter and almond butter!â (paragraphs 1 and 2). Interestingly enough, this much-needed energy enabled the players to beat Finland 3-1! When athletesâ bodies are fueled with the proper kind and amount of nutrients, there is no limit to how many gold medals they will be able to win!   </p>
<p>Dacula, GA<br />
Age 16</p>

